"{\"value\":{\"mdx\":\"# Security\\n\\nVerifying the ZCAM proof guarantees that the photo was taken using the mobile camera through the ZCAM sdk. This in turn guarantees that the photo is not AI generated.\\n\\nThis is built on the following:\\n\\n- The photo was signed using an Apple Attested private key in the secure enclave\\n    - The only way this private key signs an image is using the SDK (specifically the  `takePhoto` method)\\n    - **This is easily spoofable, anyone can make an equivalent looking photo with a valid looking manifest etc**\\n        - It's important to check the actual apple attest attestation\\n        - The final proof/ verification verifies the Apple app attestation of the key which ensures it's a valid apple app attest key tied to our app\\n- A C2PA manifest is signed using a secure enclave key\\n    - But this key isn't really bound/ identified to anything\\n- Our security assumption is that any photo that is signed using the device key was taken using the iPhone camera *through* the SDK and has not been tampered between the taking the actual picture and signing the picture.\\n- How do we ensure people are convinced the app attested key is *from our SDK/ App*.\\n    - Are we okay with this *not* being permissionless? Can lean harder on the backend then, could make it easier to scale\\n\\nWe assume that the secure enclave keys (especially the device/ apple attested key) can not be exfiltrated from the device.\\n\\nWe need to guarantee that the SDK code cannot be tampered with (both in CI and on device) to inject malicious code before signing the photo.\\n\\nWe're currently assuming *if* a photo has been signed with an Apple attested key *then* it must be authentic.\\n\\n- Clearly, this is not necessarily true, in a general case, a malicious app can be deployed that signs AI generated images, then attempts to get it proven\\n- For the ZCAM app specifically, this *may* be okay (albeit flimsy) if we can guarantee that app and SDK code have not been tampered with\\n\",\"document\":[{\"href\":\"/security#security\",\"html\":\"</header>\\n<p>Verifying the ZCAM proof guarantees that the photo was taken using the mobile camera through the ZCAM sdk. This in turn guarantees that the photo is not AI generated.</p>\\n<p>This is built on the following:</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>The photo was signed using an Apple Attested private key in the secure enclave\\n<ul>\\n<li>The only way this private key signs an image is using the SDK (specifically the  <code>takePhoto</code> method)</li>\\n<li>\\n<strong>This is easily spoofable, anyone can make an equivalent looking photo with a valid looking manifest etc</strong>\\n<ul>\\n<li>It&#x27;s important to check the actual apple attest attestation</li>\\n<li>The final proof/ verification verifies the Apple app attestation of the key which ensures it&#x27;s a valid apple app attest key tied to our app</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n<li>A C2PA manifest is signed using a secure enclave key\\n<ul>\\n<li>But this key isn&#x27;t really bound/ identified to anything</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n<li>Our security assumption is that any photo that is signed using the device key was taken using the iPhone camera <em>through</em> the SDK and has not been tampered between the taking the actual picture and signing the picture.</li>\\n<li>How do we ensure people are convinced the app attested key is <em>from our SDK/ App</em>.\\n<ul>\\n<li>Are we okay with this <em>not</em> being permissionless? Can lean harder on the backend then, could make it easier to scale</li>\\n</ul>\\n</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>We assume that the secure enclave keys (especially the device/ apple attested key) can not be exfiltrated from the device.</p>\\n<p>We need to guarantee that the SDK code cannot be tampered with (both in CI and on device) to inject malicious code before signing the photo.</p>\\n<p>We&#x27;re currently assuming <em>if</em> a photo has been signed with an Apple attested key <em>then</em> it must be authentic.</p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Clearly, this is not necessarily true, in a general case, a malicious app can be deployed that signs AI generated images, then attempts to get it proven</li>\\n<li>For the ZCAM app specifically, this <em>may</em> be okay (albeit flimsy) if we can guarantee that app and SDK code have not been tampered with</li>\\n</ul>\",\"id\":\"docs/pages/security.mdx#security\",\"isPage\":true,\"text\":\"\\nVerifying the ZCAM proof guarantees that the photo was taken using the mobile camera through the ZCAM sdk. This in turn guarantees that the photo is not AI generated.\\nThis is built on the following:\\n\\nThe photo was signed using an Apple Attested private key in the secure enclave\\n\\nThe only way this private key signs an image is using the SDK (specifically the  takePhoto method)\\n\\nThis is easily spoofable, anyone can make an equivalent looking photo with a valid looking manifest etc\\n\\nIt&#x27;s important to check the actual apple attest attestation\\nThe final proof/ verification verifies the Apple app attestation of the key which ensures it&#x27;s a valid apple app attest key tied to our app\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nA C2PA manifest is signed using a secure enclave key\\n\\nBut this key isn&#x27;t really bound/ identified to anything\\n\\n\\nOur security assumption is that any photo that is signed using the device key was taken using the iPhone camera through the SDK and has not been tampered between the taking the actual picture and signing the picture.\\nHow do we ensure people are convinced the app attested key is from our SDK/ App.\\n\\nAre we okay with this not being permissionless? Can lean harder on the backend then, could make it easier to scale\\n\\n\\n\\nWe assume that the secure enclave keys (especially the device/ apple attested key) can not be exfiltrated from the device.\\nWe need to guarantee that the SDK code cannot be tampered with (both in CI and on device) to inject malicious code before signing the photo.\\nWe&#x27;re currently assuming if a photo has been signed with an Apple attested key then it must be authentic.\\n\\nClearly, this is not necessarily true, in a general case, a malicious app can be deployed that signs AI generated images, then attempts to get it proven\\nFor the ZCAM app specifically, this may be okay (albeit flimsy) if we can guarantee that app and SDK code have not been tampered with\\n\",\"title\":\"Security\",\"titles\":[]}]}}"
